<h2>Why Dana Point Dryers Fail More Often Near the Harbour</h2>
<p>Dana Point has approximately 30% more thermal fuse failures than comparably-sized inland OC cities. The reason is specific: harbour salt air combines with lint to create a paste-like buildup in vent duct bends that standard cleaning misses. Dry inland lint clears completely in a single pass. Coastal lint — particularly near the Dana Point Harbour basin — is impregnated with salt moisture and forms a semi-adhesive material that bonds to duct wall surfaces. A standard single-pass vent cleaning removes the loose material but leaves the bonded paste on the walls, reducing airflow by 20–30% immediately after the "cleaning." The dryer runs hot against that residual restriction. Three months later, the fuse blows again. We use extended two-pass cleaning procedures on Lantern District and Harbour area calls, measure airflow before and after, and don't leave until the reading meets LG's minimum specification for the model installed.</p>

